Problem Statement¶

A US-based housing company named Surprise Housing has decided to enter the Australian market. The company uses data analytics to purchase houses at a price below their actual values and flip them on at a higher price. For the same purpose, the company has collected a data set from the sale of houses in Australia. The data is provided in the CSV file below.

The company is looking at prospective properties to buy to enter the market. You are required to build a regression model using regularisation in order to predict the actual value of the prospective properties and decide whether to invest in them or not.

The company wants to know:

Which variables are significant in predicting the price of a house, and

How well those variables describe the price of a house.

Also, determine the optimal value of lambda for ridge and lasso regression.

#replace col value which is less contributing that is any value less than 5% in that particular category will convert to other
def convertLessContributingColValuestoOther(category_cols):
    global data
    for col in category_cols:
        lessVarianceCol =[]
        data_var = round(100*(data[col].value_counts()/data.shape[0]),2).to_frame('Count')
        for i in data_var.index:
            if data_var.loc[i].Count < 5.00:
                lessVarianceCol.append(i)
        for col_val in lessVarianceCol:
            data = data.replace({col:{col_val:'Other'}})
        
        print("================"+col+"========================")
        print(data[col].value_counts())

Convert Categorical variable into dummy columns¶

In [81]:
#drop other column just formed as this is the combination of differnet cat value which is contributing very less
def dropOtherColValUsingOther(category_cols):
    global data
    for col in category_cols:
        try:
            temp_data = pd.get_dummies(data[col],prefix=col)
            temp_data = temp_data.drop(col+'_Other',axis=1)
            data = pd.concat([data,temp_data],axis=1)
            data = data.drop(col,axis=1)
        except:
            print(col)
            temp_data = pd.get_dummies(data[col],prefix=col,drop_first=True)
            data = pd.concat([data,temp_data],axis=1)
            data = data.drop(col,axis=1)

Analysis of the above graph¶

Train Score¶

As the alpha (lambda) increases, the r2 score decreases. That means the error increases. Because the model becomes less overfitting and more generalised. Thus by increasing the alpha the model becomes more simple.¶

Test Score¶

With the very lower value of alpha, the error is high as we can see the r2 value decreased. But the error for the train set is low. It means that the model is clearly overfitting with very low value of alpha. With the increasing value of alpha, the error started decreasing more and it reached to a peak at alpha=10. Here, the error is least and accuracy (r2 score) is the highest. After alpha=10, the r2 score started decreasing as the alpha is increasing. Hence, the model accuracy started dipping. We need to pick the value of aplha for which the test score peaks up.

So, the optimum alpha will be 10, for which we will have a right balance between the error and the generalisation of the model for creting a simpler model.¶

Train ( .87) & test (.85) accuracy ( measured in terms of r2) is good¶

plt.show()

Analysis of the above graph¶

From the above graph we can see that with very lower value of alpha (almost colse to 0) the accuracy of the train and test set is the highest. Coincidentally they both are alomost same.

Train Score : 83%

As the alpha (lambda) increases, the r2 score decreases. That means the error increases. Because the model becomes less overfitting and more generalised. At 0.001 (close to 0) the train set accury is highest(more than 80%).

Test Score : 81%

At alpha = 0.001 the test accuracy is highest (more than 80%). After alpha=0.001, the r2 score started decreasing as the alpha is increasing. Hence, the model accuracy started dipping. We need to pick the value of aplha for which the test score peaks up. In this case at alpha=0.001, the error is least in the test set and hence the accuracy is more approximately 81%.

So, the optimum alpha will be 0.001, for which we will have a right balance between the error and the generalisation of the model for creating a simpler model.
